MUMBAI, Jan. 10 (Xinhua) -- The art and archaeology museum in Indian city Mumbai turned 100 years old on Monday, said a statement by the government's Press Information Bureau. The museum named the Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Vastu Sangrahalaya (CSMVS), opened its doors to the public on Jan. 10, 1922, though the idea was germinated in the year 1904 by a few enthusiastic citizens of the city. Over the past century, the museum's wide-ranging collections have grown to about 70,000 objects, telling the human story, especially of the Indian subcontinent, right from pre-historic time to the present. The museum in India's financial capital collaborates with various other institutes and organizes several exhibitions and lectures.  â– 